# gen165 (E1 reflexive): proof that the composition self-challenge names parts
# DERIVED from the live module(X) self-model, not a fixed triple. Retracting
# module(abduce) drops abduction from the named parts — the next composable-core
# module, calibration, takes its place. The proposal reads the same fact base
# "who is a module?" reads; change the facts, the proposal changes.
> forget that abduce is a module
< Forgotten: module(abduce).
> how would you prove that your subsystems compose?
< I would treat it as a composition self-challenge, not self-management: from my own module set I would pick three parts I actually have — knowledge (facts and rules), robustness (which facts are load-bearing), and calibration (how sure I am) — and write ONE held-out dialogue, with fresh names so it cannot be memorized, that needs all three at once; it passes only if they cooperate with no new special-case module. I would ratchet it in English and Italian, bump my version, and journal whether composition held or a seam appeared. I can propose this; an external agent edits, runs the tests, and commits.
